{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3f657c89-5184-4912-ae39-6dbf72c7bcb5","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` ties the lifetime to an **HTTP request** — each request gets a fresh instance. In MAUI, there's no equivalent request boundary. The app essentially runs in a **single long-lived scope**, so `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton` — your DbContext is reused across all navigations.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — creates a new instance each time it's injected.\n2. **Use `IServiceScopeFactory`** to manually create scopes when you need them:\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyViewModel\n{\n    private readonly IServiceScopeFactory _scopeFactory;\n\n    public MyViewModel(IServiceScopeFactory scopeFactory)\n        => _scopeFactory = scopeFactory;\n\n    public async Task LoadData()\n    {\n        using var scope = _scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n        var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n        // db is fresh and disposed at end of block\n    }\n}\n```\n\n`AddTransient` is the simplest fix; manual scopes give you more control over the lifetime boundary.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"07911887-a8cb-4e2e-ac2f-9931087fa0a6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no equivalent of an HTTP request to define a scope boundary. MAUI apps typically have a single scope for the entire application lifetime, making `AddScoped` behave effectively like `AddSingleton`.","outputTokens":431,"requestId":"483C:1E3288:9D154A:B88585:69F3FD44"},"id":"c73beb25-9648-45c3-b123-db9024d082e9","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:09:34.468Z","parentId":"be2fd9c1-9a76-4a99-a6b3-2546ac9c38dd"}
